WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.660
In this video we're going to talk about organic chemistry.

00:00:04.540 --> 00:00:11.119
Now this video is for those of you who are taking the first semester of organic chemistry in college.

00:00:12.580 --> 00:00:15.199
Organic chemistry focuses on organic compounds.

00:00:15.500 --> 00:00:17.859
Compounds that contain carbon atoms.

00:00:19.120 --> 00:00:21.339
Now carbon elects the form for bonds.

00:00:22.399 --> 00:00:27.399
But you also need to know the number of bonds that the other elements elect a form.

00:00:27.399 --> 00:00:34.359
So elements in the first group of the pair of table like hydrogen, they like to form one bond.

00:00:35.179 --> 00:00:38.219
Beryllium for example likes to form two bonds.

00:00:40.500 --> 00:00:44.939
Boron which has three valence electrons, it likes to form three bonds.

00:00:46.020 --> 00:00:51.420
Carbon has four valence electrons. Carbon likes to form four bonds.

00:00:54.640 --> 00:00:57.259
Nitrogen likes to form three bonds.

00:00:58.039 --> 00:01:01.520
Organic chemistry. Oxygen likes to form two.

00:01:04.040 --> 00:01:05.379
And elements like fluorine.

00:01:06.579 --> 00:01:11.200
And the other hyalurgyns chlorine bromine iodine, they like to form one bond.

00:01:12.140 --> 00:01:15.599
Now there are cases where chlorine bromine and iodine conform seven bonds.

00:01:17.140 --> 00:01:19.840
But we're really not going to cover that in this video.

00:01:19.840 --> 00:01:24.459
I do have another video on how to Lewis structures which goes into that detail.

00:01:24.859 --> 00:01:25.879
For those of you who might be curious.

00:01:27.420 --> 00:01:31.799
Now understanding that this is important because it helps us to draw Lewis structures.

00:01:33.579 --> 00:01:38.920
So for instance, let's say if we want to draw the Lewis structure of water, H2O.

00:01:39.920 --> 00:01:46.079
And no one that oxygen likes to form two bonds and hydrogen likes to form one,

00:01:46.079 --> 00:01:48.560
we can start with a structure that looks like this.

00:01:50.219 --> 00:01:53.180
Now oxygen likes to have eight electrons.

00:01:53.859 --> 00:01:55.560
Each bond represents two electrons.

00:01:56.359 --> 00:01:57.379
So that's a total of four.

00:01:57.980 --> 00:02:00.680
To get to eight, we need to add two lumpers.

00:02:01.700 --> 00:02:03.659
So that is the Lewis structure for water.

00:02:05.079 --> 00:02:12.319
Now the bond between hydrogen and oxygen is known as an H bond or a hydrogen bond.

00:02:12.319 --> 00:02:15.099
Which is a special type of covalent bond.

00:02:15.960 --> 00:02:21.439
Hydrogen bonds occur whenever H is directly attached to nitrogen, oxygen or fluorine.

00:02:22.800 --> 00:02:26.759
Hydrogen bond and explains why water has such a high bonus point.

00:02:27.900 --> 00:02:30.300
Now let's say if we have methyl fluoride.

00:02:31.159 --> 00:02:34.319
How can we draw the Lewis structure for that molecule?

00:02:36.140 --> 00:02:39.340
So we know that carbon likes to form four bonds.

00:02:39.340 --> 00:02:40.539
So we're going to put that in the middle.

00:02:41.319 --> 00:02:43.280
Hydrogen likes to form one bond.

00:02:44.759 --> 00:02:46.639
Fluorine also likes to form one bond.

00:02:46.819 --> 00:02:48.659
So this is the best Lewis structure that we can make.

00:02:50.360 --> 00:02:55.780
And if you want, you can add three lumpers to fluorine so that it has eight electrons around it.

00:02:56.280 --> 00:03:02.099
Elements in the second row, like carbon, nitrogen, oxygen, and fluorine, they like to have eight electrons.

00:03:02.719 --> 00:03:08.759
They don't always have to have eight, but ideally speaking, they like to have eight.

00:03:08.759 --> 00:03:10.099
So that they can be stable.

00:03:10.939 --> 00:03:12.840
But that's the structure of methyl fluoride.

00:03:14.800 --> 00:03:18.340
Now the carbon fluorine bond is a polar bond.

00:03:20.319 --> 00:03:24.240
Carbon has an electron negativity value of 2.5.

00:03:25.379 --> 00:03:28.699
And the electron negativity value of fluorine is 4.0.

00:03:30.180 --> 00:03:36.680
Whenever the electron negativity difference between two elements is 0.5 or more, the bond is sent to be polar.

00:03:36.680 --> 00:03:39.419
So this is a polar bond.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:44.460
It's not a hydrogen bond because fluorine is not directly attached to hydrogen.

00:03:45.379 --> 00:03:47.199
But it's a polar covalent bond.

00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:51.280
Now you might be wondering, what does it mean for a bond to be polar?

00:03:52.840 --> 00:03:58.780
A polarized object is an object that is neutral overall, but has charge separation.

00:03:59.280 --> 00:04:02.300
That is one side is positive and the other side is negative.

00:04:02.300 --> 00:04:06.039
So this is a polarized object.

00:04:07.659 --> 00:04:13.240
The bond is polar because fluorine carries a partial negative charge.

00:04:13.560 --> 00:04:16.959
Due to the fact that it's more electronegative than carbon.

00:04:17.459 --> 00:04:19.100
So it pulls electrons toward itself.

00:04:19.839 --> 00:04:24.259
And carbon being less electronegative has a partial positive charge.

00:04:25.019 --> 00:04:30.500
So due to that charge separation, we can say that the carbon fluorine bond is polar.

00:04:31.599 --> 00:04:35.360
Now the carbon hydrogen bond, that's a non-polar bond.

00:04:35.879 --> 00:04:42.699
The reason being is the electronegativity difference between carbon and hydrogen is less than 0.5.

00:04:45.240 --> 00:04:48.779
Carbon, we said, it's electronegative value is 2.5.

00:04:49.180 --> 00:04:50.399
Hydrogen is 2.1.

00:04:51.019 --> 00:04:55.279
So the difference between it two is 0.4.

00:04:56.279 --> 00:05:05.759
So understand this, anytime you see a hydrocarbon or a bond that contains carbon and hydrogen, those bonds are non-polar bonds.

00:05:06.560 --> 00:05:11.100
Because sometimes you need to determine if a molecule is polar or non-polar.

00:05:11.759 --> 00:05:18.600
So for instance, in methane, CH4, that's a non-polar molecule because it only contains carbon and hydrogen.

00:05:19.759 --> 00:05:23.839
So far we've considered two types of covalent bonds.

00:05:24.819 --> 00:05:30.019
Polar covalent bonds and another special type which are hydrogen bonds.

00:05:32.060 --> 00:05:36.240
And we also talked about non-polar covalent bonds like the carbon hydrogen bond.

00:05:36.420 --> 00:05:37.779
That's a non-polar covalent bond.

00:05:38.959 --> 00:05:44.939
But you need to understand the difference between a covalent bond and an ionic bond.

00:05:47.819 --> 00:05:50.800
In a covalent bond, the electrons are being shared.

00:05:50.800 --> 00:05:53.839
They can be shared equally or unequally.

00:05:54.660 --> 00:06:03.379
So in the case of the hydrogen molecule H2, the electrons in this bond are being shared equally between these two atoms.

00:06:04.019 --> 00:06:05.180
Because the atoms are identical.

00:06:05.839 --> 00:06:13.779
So that's known as a non-polar covalent bond, which I put Cb for covalent bond.

00:06:13.779 --> 00:06:21.279
In the case of hydrogen fluoride, that is a polar covalent bond.

00:06:23.420 --> 00:06:26.339
Hydrogen has an electron negativity of 2.1.

00:06:26.920 --> 00:06:29.759
Floring has a value of 4.0.

00:06:31.100 --> 00:06:33.779
So hydrogen is going to be partially positive.

00:06:34.399 --> 00:06:35.920
Floring will be partially negative.

00:06:37.120 --> 00:06:40.980
And this is a special type of polar covalent bond. That's a hydrogen bond.

00:06:42.339 --> 00:06:44.939
So those are some two examples of covalent bond.

00:06:45.120 --> 00:06:49.639
You have non-polar covalent bonds and polar covalent bonds.

00:06:50.220 --> 00:06:52.019
So make sure you understand the difference here.

00:06:52.639 --> 00:06:56.259
The electrons are shared equally as the keyword.

00:06:58.939 --> 00:07:02.620
And in this case, the electrons are shared unequally.

00:07:04.500 --> 00:07:07.120
Floring is going to have a tighter hold on those electrons.

00:07:08.160 --> 00:07:10.100
Now let's talk about ionic bonds.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:15.920
So in an ionic bond, the electrons are not shared. They're transferred.

00:07:16.620 --> 00:07:20.639
A good example is the reaction between sodium metal and chlorine.

00:07:21.540 --> 00:07:23.620
Sodium has one valence electron.

00:07:24.319 --> 00:07:25.420
Chlorine has seven.

00:07:30.420 --> 00:07:35.779
Sodium is a metal and chlorine is a non-metal.

00:07:35.779 --> 00:07:40.540
Metals like to give away their electrons because they're a electro-positive.

00:07:41.300 --> 00:07:46.579
Not metals like to accept or acquire electrons because they're electronegative.

00:07:47.399 --> 00:07:51.779
So sodium is going to give one electron to chlorine.

00:07:52.680 --> 00:07:55.480
A half-arrow represents the flow of one electron.

00:07:55.920 --> 00:07:58.759
A full-arrow represents the flow of two electrons.

00:08:01.719 --> 00:08:07.259
So in this reaction, sodium is going to turn into the sodium plus ion,

00:08:07.879 --> 00:08:09.279
which is known as a cation.

00:08:10.100 --> 00:08:12.399
Positively charged ions are called cations.

00:08:13.379 --> 00:08:17.980
Now chlorine, when it acquires an electron, it becomes chloride.

00:08:18.860 --> 00:08:23.040
So now it has eight electrons. It's going to now have a negative charge.

00:08:26.299 --> 00:08:29.360
Negatively charged ions are known as anions.

00:08:32.100 --> 00:08:36.799
Now going back to physics, you know that opposite charges attract one another.

00:08:38.080 --> 00:08:44.100
So a positively charged ion will fill a force of attraction to a negatively charged ion.

00:08:44.840 --> 00:08:47.120
So these two charges, they're attracted to each other.

00:08:47.120 --> 00:08:56.039
And that force of attraction, that electrostatic force, is what keeps the ions in an ionic crystal together.

00:08:57.180 --> 00:09:04.240
So that creates that ionic bond, that electrostatic force of attraction that pulls the sodium and the chloride ions together.

00:09:05.799 --> 00:09:10.240
So now you know the difference between an ionic bond and a covalent bond.

00:09:12.340 --> 00:09:17.240
So now we're going to spend some time drawing Lewis structures of certain organic compounds.

00:09:17.820 --> 00:09:22.019
But before we do, let's talk about some common names of alkains.

00:09:24.040 --> 00:09:30.940
Alcains are saturated organic compounds, mean that the carbon atoms are filled with hydrogen atoms.

00:09:32.560 --> 00:09:39.919
Methane is a one carbon alkane. It's M-E-T-H-A-N-E.

00:09:40.539 --> 00:09:45.600
A two carbon alkane, C2H6, this is known as ethane.

00:09:49.100 --> 00:09:52.120
C3H8, this is called propane.

00:09:56.720 --> 00:10:00.399
C4H10, this is known as butane.

00:10:03.120 --> 00:10:09.539
So alkains generally follow this formula, CNH2N plus 2.

00:10:13.120 --> 00:10:16.759
So a five carbon alkane will have 12 hydrogen atoms.

00:10:18.240 --> 00:10:23.019
If N is 5, then it's going to be H2 times 5 plus 2.

00:10:23.379 --> 00:10:24.779
So that's 10 plus 2 you get 12.

00:10:26.019 --> 00:10:29.100
A five carbon alkane is known as pentane.

00:10:30.259 --> 00:10:33.759
A six carbon alkane is known as hexane.

00:10:34.700 --> 00:10:35.940
You may want to take some notes by the way.

00:10:37.779 --> 00:10:40.259
Because you'll need to know this at least up to 10.

00:10:41.080 --> 00:10:44.620
The seven carbon alkane, that's heptane.

00:10:47.540 --> 00:10:50.480
Next we have octane.

00:10:55.160 --> 00:10:58.220
And then after that, this is, that's a 20.

00:10:59.340 --> 00:11:00.539
This is nonane.

00:11:01.320 --> 00:11:02.759
Or if you're going to call it nonane.

00:11:03.519 --> 00:11:07.600
And then C10H22, that's known as decane.

00:11:10.259 --> 00:11:14.620
Now let's talk about how to draw the Lewis structure of C2H6.

00:11:17.400 --> 00:11:19.279
C2H6, we know that's ethane.

00:11:20.379 --> 00:11:22.639
And you can write the condensed structure like this.

00:11:23.279 --> 00:11:25.080
It's CH3, CH3.

00:11:25.940 --> 00:11:30.059
So this tells you how many hydrogen atoms are on each carbon.

00:11:30.820 --> 00:11:33.360
First carbon has three hydrogen atoms.

00:11:34.480 --> 00:11:39.179
And that's attached to the second carbon, which also has

00:11:39.179 --> 00:11:40.940
three hydrogen atoms.

00:11:41.879 --> 00:11:44.460
So that's how you can draw the Lewis structure of ethane.

00:11:46.680 --> 00:11:49.259
Now what about C2H4?

00:11:50.620 --> 00:11:52.539
How would you draw the Lewis structure for that?

00:11:57.180 --> 00:12:06.179
So this time each carbon atom is going to have two hydrogen atoms instead of three.

00:12:07.559 --> 00:12:13.179
Because it's a total of four and you want to make sure that the four hydrogen atoms are distributed equally.

00:12:14.500 --> 00:12:17.139
So what bond do we need between the two carbon atoms?

00:12:18.580 --> 00:12:21.440
Well we know that carbon likes the form four bonds.

00:12:22.299 --> 00:12:27.659
So the only way this is going to happen is if we put a double bond between the two carbon atoms.

00:12:28.779 --> 00:12:31.179
And so this is known as an alkene.

00:12:33.360 --> 00:12:35.539
Alchene's contain at least one double bond.

00:12:36.660 --> 00:12:38.899
Alchene's do not contain double bonds.

00:12:39.860 --> 00:12:43.480
So a two carbon alkene is known as ethane.

00:12:46.500 --> 00:12:47.740
Now what about this one?

00:12:48.480 --> 00:12:49.039
C2H2.

00:12:49.820 --> 00:12:51.519
How can we draw the Lewis structure for that?

00:12:53.960 --> 00:12:57.379
Well we have a total of two hydrogen atoms.

00:12:58.120 --> 00:13:00.820
So we're going to put one hydrogen atom on each carbon.

00:13:01.620 --> 00:13:07.399
And in order for the two carbon atoms to have four bonds, we need to put a triple bond in the middle.

00:13:07.820 --> 00:13:09.639
Because carbon likes to form four bonds.

00:13:10.700 --> 00:13:16.960
And so whatever you have a hydrocarbon with a triple bond, you now have what is known as an alkene.

00:13:17.740 --> 00:13:20.980
A two carbon alkene is known as ethane.

00:13:23.120 --> 00:13:26.659
The common name for this is acetylene.

00:13:28.080 --> 00:13:31.759
And the common name for this compound is known as ethane.

00:13:38.419 --> 00:13:43.500
Alchene's and alchene's are known as unsaturated compounds.

00:13:44.340 --> 00:13:48.379
Because they don't contain the maximum number of hydrogen atoms per carbon atom.

00:13:49.460 --> 00:13:52.720
Alchene's are known as saturated compounds.

00:13:53.759 --> 00:13:55.259
So make sure you keep this in mind.

00:13:56.620 --> 00:13:59.259
Now let's focus on the carbon carbon bonds.

00:14:00.880 --> 00:14:04.960
What would you say which of these bonds is the longest bond?

00:14:06.019 --> 00:14:11.139
The carbon carbon single bond, the double bond, or the carbon carbon triple bond.

00:14:12.620 --> 00:14:13.980
Which one is the longest?

00:14:14.980 --> 00:14:17.019
And which one is the shortest?

00:14:19.840 --> 00:14:27.200
You need to know that the carbon carbon single bond is longer than the carbon carbon double bond.

00:14:27.919 --> 00:14:30.799
And that's longer than the carbon carbon triple bond.

00:14:32.500 --> 00:14:41.980
The left of the carbon carbon single bond is 154 pkm, which is 1.54 angstroms.

00:14:42.980 --> 00:14:44.299
One angstrom is 100 pkm.

00:14:45.120 --> 00:14:50.080
The CC double bond is 133 pkm in ethane.

00:14:50.919 --> 00:14:56.200
And in ethane, I mean ethane, it's 120.

00:14:58.139 --> 00:15:02.200
So what you need to understand is that triple bonds are short bonds,

00:15:02.879 --> 00:15:06.320
whereas single bonds are long bonds.

00:15:06.320 --> 00:15:10.399
Because sometimes you may get a test question that asks you something about bond lift.

00:15:10.600 --> 00:15:14.220
Which of these bonds is the shortest or which of these bonds is the longest?

00:15:15.480 --> 00:15:18.220
So single bonds are longer than triple bonds.

00:15:18.320 --> 00:15:18.919
Keep that in mind.

00:15:20.659 --> 00:15:25.659
So now that we've talked about bond lift, let's talk about bond strength.

00:15:26.740 --> 00:15:28.519
Which bond is the strongest?

00:15:29.360 --> 00:15:32.259
The single bond, the double bond, or the triple bond?

00:15:32.500 --> 00:15:33.039
What would you say?

00:15:34.559 --> 00:15:37.399
The single bond is the weakest.

00:15:39.480 --> 00:15:42.340
The triple bond is the strongest.

00:15:43.980 --> 00:15:44.879
Why is that?

00:15:45.960 --> 00:15:50.340
Well, it's easier to break one bond instead of three bonds.

00:15:51.700 --> 00:15:53.279
Imagine trying to break a pencil.

00:15:53.559 --> 00:15:57.980
It's easier breaking one pencil than trying to break three pencils at a time.

00:15:58.600 --> 00:15:59.860
Three bonds are stronger than one.

00:16:03.740 --> 00:16:06.639
Now let's talk about sigma and pi bonds.

00:16:08.820 --> 00:16:13.320
A single bond contains one sigma bond.

00:16:13.980 --> 00:16:17.240
All single bonds are sigma bonds.

00:16:18.320 --> 00:16:24.299
A double bond contains one sigma and one pi bond.

00:16:25.560 --> 00:16:31.519
The triple bond contains one sigma and two pi bonds.

00:16:32.379 --> 00:16:34.659
Now which bond is stronger?

00:16:34.860 --> 00:16:37.039
A single bond or a pi bond?

00:16:38.540 --> 00:16:43.019
You need to know that sigma bonds are stronger than pi bonds.

00:16:43.980 --> 00:16:52.360
So it's harder to break this bond versus just one of the pi bonds in the triple bond.

00:16:52.360 --> 00:16:54.580
Not all three bonds, but one of the pi bonds.

00:16:55.519 --> 00:17:01.740
So in summary, a triple bond is stronger than a single bond.

00:17:01.980 --> 00:17:03.539
Because you compare them three bonds to one.

00:17:04.740 --> 00:17:08.200
However, a single bond is stronger than a pi bond.

00:17:08.619 --> 00:17:10.579
When you compare one bond with one bond.

00:17:11.460 --> 00:17:12.740
So I'm just going to say that one more time.

00:17:12.940 --> 00:17:14.920
Sigma bonds are stronger than pi bonds.

00:17:15.480 --> 00:17:18.740
But triple bonds are stronger than single bonds.

00:17:21.440 --> 00:17:24.700
Now the next thing we're going to talk about is bond order.

00:17:31.620 --> 00:17:34.839
What is the bond order for a single bond?

00:17:35.460 --> 00:17:36.940
A double bond and a triple bond.

00:17:37.559 --> 00:17:38.900
This one is pretty straightforward.

00:17:39.720 --> 00:17:42.359
For a single bond, the bond order is one.

00:17:43.259 --> 00:17:46.000
For a double bond, the bond order is two.

00:17:46.500 --> 00:17:48.960
And for a triple bond, the bond order is three.

00:17:50.039 --> 00:17:52.140
So that's just something to know.

00:17:53.519 --> 00:17:55.119
Now let's talk about hybridization.

00:17:56.119 --> 00:18:00.440
What is the hybridization of the carbon atoms highlighted in green?

00:18:02.180 --> 00:18:11.440
Would you say it's s, s p 2, s p 3, s p ds p 3, d 2, s p 3, what would you say?

00:18:12.859 --> 00:18:26.259
A quick and simple way to determine the hybridization around a certain carbon atom is to count the number of atoms attached to that particular carbon atom and the number of long periods that it has.

00:18:27.259 --> 00:18:32.019
So this particular carbon atom is attached to four other atoms.

00:18:33.019 --> 00:18:36.059
So you can think of it as having four groups around it.

00:18:36.720 --> 00:18:41.839
So the hybridization is going to be s 1 p 3 because the exponent is added up to four.

00:18:42.880 --> 00:18:49.019
Now let's say if we want to determine the hybridization of this carbon atom, that carbon is attached to three other atoms.

00:18:50.059 --> 00:18:51.799
So it has three groups around it.

00:18:52.339 --> 00:18:56.859
The hybridization is going to be s 1 p 2 or s p 2 hybridized.

00:18:58.100 --> 00:19:04.599
And then for this particular alkyne, the carbon atom has two atoms attached to it.

00:19:05.519 --> 00:19:08.700
So if the two groups is going to be s p hybridized.

00:19:09.460 --> 00:19:13.799
So that's a quick and simple way to determine the hybridization of a carbon atom.

00:19:17.120 --> 00:19:18.200
Here's a question for you.

00:19:18.920 --> 00:19:23.380
So let's say we have a Lewis structure that looks like this.

00:19:31.980 --> 00:19:38.900
What is the hybridization of not the atoms but the bond?

00:19:39.160 --> 00:19:46.640
What is the hybridization of the CH bond and also of this particular CH bond?

00:19:47.200 --> 00:19:47.799
What would you say?

00:19:49.000 --> 00:20:00.460
If you were to get a test question that asked you that question, how would you determine the hybridizations of this bond highlighted in red and this bond highlighted in blue?

00:20:03.059 --> 00:20:09.759
What you need to do is determine the hybridization of the atoms that are connected to those bonds.

00:20:10.599 --> 00:20:12.559
So what is the hybridization of this carbon atom?

00:20:13.179 --> 00:20:16.319
That carbon is attached to four other atoms.

00:20:17.519 --> 00:20:23.240
So it has four groups and so it's going to be s p 3 hybridized.

00:20:25.640 --> 00:20:27.920
Now you need to look at the other atom, the hydrogen.

00:20:29.240 --> 00:20:31.440
Hydrogen is only attached to one atom.

00:20:32.099 --> 00:20:34.500
So what do you think the hybridization of hydrogen is going to be?

00:20:35.619 --> 00:20:36.980
This is going to be s.

00:20:37.620 --> 00:20:40.859
So that's the hybridization of the CH bond.

00:20:41.319 --> 00:20:45.220
That's going to be s p 3 dash s.

00:20:45.839 --> 00:20:48.140
You simply just write both of these together.

00:20:50.980 --> 00:20:53.720
Now what about the CH bond highlighted in blue?

00:20:54.440 --> 00:20:56.480
What is the hybridization of that CH bond?

