So let's start with the carbon atom.

00:21:02.599 --> 00:21:06.460
That carbon is attached to two other atoms.

00:21:06.799 --> 00:21:13.740
So it's going to be s p hybridized and hydrogen is always s hybridized.

00:21:14.579 --> 00:21:20.400
So that particular CH bond is going to be s p dash s hybridized.

00:21:22.359 --> 00:21:31.819
Now another question that you might be asking given this compound is how many sigma and pi bonds are in this compound?

00:21:33.120 --> 00:21:36.960
Feel free to pause the video and try it.

00:21:38.980 --> 00:21:42.099
So first let's count the number of sigma bonds.

00:21:42.880 --> 00:21:45.359
Every single bond is a sigma bond.

00:21:45.839 --> 00:21:52.299
So we have one, two, three, four, five, and there's one sigma bond in the triple bond.

00:21:52.740 --> 00:21:56.059
So we have a total of six sigma bonds.

00:21:57.960 --> 00:21:59.720
Now how many pi bonds do we have?

00:22:00.480 --> 00:22:06.480
We know that a double bond contains one pi bond, a triple bond contains two pi bonds.

00:22:07.660 --> 00:22:11.980
So this molecule have six sigma bonds and two pi bonds.

00:22:12.680 --> 00:22:17.700
So that's how you can determine the number of sigma and pi bonds in an organic compound.

00:22:18.860 --> 00:22:25.099
Now the next topic of discussion is how to calculate the formal charge of an element.

00:22:26.360 --> 00:22:29.079
So let's use carbon as an example.

00:22:31.759 --> 00:22:39.480
Calculate the formal charge of each carbon atom for these three situations.

00:22:47.300 --> 00:22:51.440
If you know how to do it, feel free to go ahead and try it.

00:22:51.440 --> 00:22:55.579
Now this is a formula that will help you to calculate the formal charge of an atom.

00:22:56.420 --> 00:22:57.019
And here it is.

00:22:57.559 --> 00:23:03.880
The formal charge is going to be equal to the number of valence electrons of the element,

00:23:06.020 --> 00:23:10.779
minus the number of bonds and dots attached to the element.

00:23:12.059 --> 00:23:17.200
So for the first example, carbon has four bonds.

00:23:17.200 --> 00:23:19.319
I mean, let me say it again.

00:23:19.440 --> 00:23:20.900
Carbon has four valence electrons.

00:23:21.519 --> 00:23:24.240
It's in group 4a of the periodic table.

00:23:25.359 --> 00:23:31.180
And in this example, it has three bonds, one, two, three, and it doesn't have any dots around it.

00:23:32.420 --> 00:23:34.299
So four minus three is one.

00:23:35.759 --> 00:23:39.759
So this particular carbon atom has a formal charge of plus one.

00:23:40.240 --> 00:23:42.420
So we could say that it has a positive formal charge.

00:23:44.080 --> 00:23:53.259
Now moving on to the next one, it's going to be four valence electrons, minus three bonds, and one dot.

00:23:55.759 --> 00:24:00.279
So we got three bonds, one dot, that's four minus four, so that's zero.

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:02.259
So this one is neutral.

00:24:02.740 --> 00:24:03.619
It doesn't have a charge.

00:24:06.480 --> 00:24:11.339
Now for the last example on the right, the valence electrons of carbon will still be the same.

00:24:11.980 --> 00:24:15.039
We still have three bonds, but this time we have two dots.

00:24:15.980 --> 00:24:17.980
One lone pair is equivalent to two dots.

00:24:18.900 --> 00:24:20.420
So three plus two is five.

00:24:21.160 --> 00:24:23.420
Four minus five is negative one.

00:24:24.420 --> 00:24:28.119
So this particular carbon atom has a negative charge.

00:24:30.159 --> 00:24:42.079
We said that positive, let me say that again, we said that positively charged ions are called cations, and negatively charged ions are known as anion.

00:24:42.759 --> 00:24:47.180
When you add a carbon to it, this is called a carbol cation.

00:24:48.180 --> 00:24:52.319
And on the right, this is called a carb anion.

00:24:53.779 --> 00:24:55.660
Carb anions have negative charges.

00:24:57.079 --> 00:25:03.900
Now when you have an odd number of electrons, you have what is known as a radical.

00:25:05.759 --> 00:25:09.180
So a one carbon radical is known as a methyl radical.

00:25:11.480 --> 00:25:12.980
Radicals tend to be neutral.

00:25:14.280 --> 00:25:16.400
Now let's work on some more examples.

00:25:17.200 --> 00:25:21.640
Go ahead and calculate the formal charge of the sulfur atom.

00:25:24.799 --> 00:25:29.660
And also calculate the formal charge of the nitrogen atom.

00:25:31.980 --> 00:25:34.200
Go ahead and take a minute to work on that example.

00:25:35.180 --> 00:25:36.480
Or those two examples rather.

00:25:37.119 --> 00:25:49.599
By the way, for those of you who are looking for a specific topic, but for some reason you're not finding it in this video, when you get a chance, do a YouTube search, type in organic chemistry playlist.

00:25:51.579 --> 00:25:55.039
I have two playlists, an older one and a newer one.

00:25:55.559 --> 00:25:56.839
The newer one is going to be more helpful.

00:25:57.880 --> 00:26:02.599
So in that playlist, chances are you'll find a topic that you might be looking for.

00:26:03.339 --> 00:26:05.539
So just feel free to take a look at that as well.

00:26:06.019 --> 00:26:16.859
I'll be posting some links in the description section below this video with some other topics that might help you with the first exam that you might be taking in organic chemistry.

00:26:17.359 --> 00:26:19.059
So feel free to check that out as well.

00:26:20.140 --> 00:26:20.819
So let's begin.

00:26:20.920 --> 00:26:21.839
Let's start with sulfur.

00:26:23.559 --> 00:26:24.619
Let's write the formula.

00:26:24.900 --> 00:26:32.460
So the formal charge is going to be the number of Vance electrons minus the sum of the bonds and dots around that element.

00:26:33.440 --> 00:26:35.559
Now how many Vance electrons does sulfur have?

00:26:36.819 --> 00:26:40.920
Sulfur is found in Group 6A of the periodic table.

00:26:41.359 --> 00:26:43.559
If you don't have one, you could do a Google search.

00:26:43.900 --> 00:26:45.299
You could find it in Google Images.

00:26:45.799 --> 00:26:47.339
And then you could pull up the periodic table.

00:26:47.339 --> 00:26:55.519
If you look for sulfur, it's right under oxygen and it's in Group 6A, which means that sulfur has 6 Vance electrons.

00:26:56.019 --> 00:26:59.819
In this structure, it only has one bond attached to it.

00:27:00.660 --> 00:27:01.920
Now how many dots does it have?

00:27:02.940 --> 00:27:07.039
Well, we have three lone pairs, which is equivalent to 6 dots.

00:27:08.259 --> 00:27:10.799
So this is 6 minus 7.

00:27:11.519 --> 00:27:15.559
So the sulfur atom has a negative one formal charge.

00:27:17.940 --> 00:27:25.200
Now for nitrogen in the ammonium ion, nitrogen has 5 Vance electrons.

00:27:25.460 --> 00:27:28.140
It's in Group 5A of the periodic table.

00:27:28.740 --> 00:27:31.420
In this structure, it has 4 bonds, no dots.

00:27:32.359 --> 00:27:33.940
So 5 mod is 4 is 1.

00:27:34.640 --> 00:27:42.339
So this particular nitrogen atom has a plus 1, or some may say a 1 plus formal charge.

00:27:43.019 --> 00:27:47.420
So that's how you could determine the formal charge of an element.

00:27:49.039 --> 00:27:57.319
Now let's go back to this structure, because there's another question that I'm going to ask that teaches another concept.

00:27:59.619 --> 00:28:07.519
How many bond in electrons and non bond in electrons are present in this ion?

00:28:08.480 --> 00:28:09.480
What would you say?

00:28:12.500 --> 00:28:26.259
A lone pair represents a pair of non bond in electrons, because they're only attached to one atom.

00:28:26.960 --> 00:28:28.339
So they're non bond in electrons.

00:28:29.540 --> 00:28:33.640
In a bond, you have two bond in electrons.

00:28:37.120 --> 00:28:43.480
So the count the number of bond in electrons, this is going to be 2, 4, 6, 8.

00:28:44.319 --> 00:28:50.359
So this particular ion has a total of 8 bond in electrons, because it has 4 bonds.

00:28:51.240 --> 00:28:54.460
Each bond contains two bond in electrons.

00:28:56.059 --> 00:28:59.460
Now how many non bond in electrons do we have?

00:29:01.460 --> 00:29:03.380
2, 4, 6.

00:29:03.980 --> 00:29:10.700
There's a total of 6 non bond in electrons, which equates to 3 lone pairs.

00:29:12.140 --> 00:29:14.140
So make sure you understand that concept.

00:29:15.140 --> 00:29:23.400
One lone pair is equal to 2 non bond in electrons, and one bond equates to 2 bonding electrons.

00:29:24.700 --> 00:29:33.980
Now let's continue our discussion of drawn the Lewis structures of organic compounds, as well as considering the functional groups of those compounds.

00:29:35.539 --> 00:29:45.500
So let's consider CH3, CH2OH, and let's compare that with CH3, CH0.

00:29:46.500 --> 00:29:51.819
So feel free to pause the video and go ahead and draw the two Lewis structures.

00:29:53.539 --> 00:30:01.259
So for the one on the left, we have a carbon that is connected to three hydrogen atoms,

00:30:01.259 --> 00:30:10.180
and then it's attached to a CH2, that is a carbon with two hydrogen atoms, and that's connected to an OH group.

00:30:10.819 --> 00:30:16.240
Keep in mind, oxygen likes to have two bonds, and it's going to have two lone pairs.

00:30:17.660 --> 00:30:19.880
So that's the Lewis structure for this molecule.

00:30:21.599 --> 00:30:27.220
Now whenever you see an OH group, this is the functional group of an alcohol.

00:30:29.439 --> 00:30:41.019
And the fact that we have two carbons, this is associated with the alkanethane, but because we have an alcohol, we can name it ethanol.

00:30:42.619 --> 00:30:46.839
So alcohols have the suffix OL, so this is ethanol.

00:30:50.579 --> 00:30:52.380
Now what about the structure on the right?

00:30:53.019 --> 00:31:00.319
So we have a methyl group that is a CH3, and that is attached to a carbon atom.

00:31:01.559 --> 00:31:04.000
Now it's CH0 instead of OH.

00:31:04.820 --> 00:31:09.599
When you see CH0, this is the functional group of an aldehyde.

00:31:11.140 --> 00:31:16.619
If we were to write OH, this is not going to work because carbon doesn't have four bonds.

00:31:18.100 --> 00:31:21.279
So that tells you that we need a different structure.

00:31:22.380 --> 00:31:31.319
An aldehyde contains a carbonyl group, which is basically a carbon double bonded to an oxygen, and then here's the hydrogen.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:43.640
So in this case, every carbon atom has four bonds, every hydrogen atom has one bond, and the oxygen atom has two bonds, which is what they usually have in neutral molecules.

00:31:44.900 --> 00:31:48.920
And of course, the oxygen is going to have two lumpiers as it did here.

00:31:50.099 --> 00:32:00.440
So this is a carbonyl, and this particular carbonyl, which is attached to a hydrogen, that is known as an aldehyde.

00:32:03.160 --> 00:32:05.099
So that's the name of the functional group.

00:32:05.099 --> 00:32:14.740
A two-carbon aldehyde is called ethanol instead of ethanol, so it ends in Al as opposed to OL.

00:32:15.559 --> 00:32:19.519
The common name for this aldehyde is acetaldehyde.

00:32:25.420 --> 00:32:27.480
Now let's consider these two examples.

00:32:29.220 --> 00:32:35.480
CH3O CH3 and CH3CO CH3.

00:32:36.340 --> 00:32:37.279
Notice the difference.

00:32:38.299 --> 00:32:41.220
So go ahead and draw the Lewis structure for these two organic compounds.

00:32:42.740 --> 00:32:51.440
For the first one, we have a methyl group, that's a carbon with three hydrogen atoms, and then we have an oxygen in the middle.

00:32:51.440 --> 00:32:57.079
As we said before, oxygen likes to form two bonds, and then another methyl group to the right of that.

00:32:58.259 --> 00:33:03.400
So this particular compound has a functional group known as an ether.

00:33:04.540 --> 00:33:10.680
An ether is basically an oxygen atom between two carbon atoms, that's an ether.

00:33:12.259 --> 00:33:17.940
Now because this particular ether has two methyl groups, one to the left, one to the right,

00:33:17.940 --> 00:33:21.480
this is known as dimethyl ether.

00:33:22.059 --> 00:33:24.119
The prefix dye means two.

00:33:24.900 --> 00:33:30.579
Try means three, tetra means four, penta means five.

00:33:32.819 --> 00:33:37.079
Now how would you draw the Lewis structure for the compound on the right?

00:33:39.680 --> 00:33:45.240
So we know that we have a methyl group on the left, and then there's a carbon atom.

00:33:45.240 --> 00:33:47.480
Now where do we put the oxygen atom?

00:33:48.200 --> 00:33:53.420
If we put it in the middle, this carbon atom is going to have two bonds.

00:33:54.559 --> 00:33:57.059
So the fixed that problem, we need to put it up here.

00:33:57.559 --> 00:34:02.940
We need to make another carbon-neil function group, and then write the methyl group.

00:34:03.460 --> 00:34:11.119
So in this case, every carbon atom has four bonds, the oxygen atom has two bonds, and every hydrogen atom has one bond.

00:34:12.340 --> 00:34:19.179
That's why it's important to know the number of bonds each element like to make, because it makes draw the Lewis structures a lot easier.

00:34:22.400 --> 00:34:30.599
Now even though we have a carbon-neil function group, the name of the function group for this particular molecule is different than an aldehyde.

00:34:31.179 --> 00:34:32.760
This is known as a ketone.

00:34:34.159 --> 00:34:37.139
When the carbonyl group is in the middle of the chain, it's a ketone.

00:34:37.559 --> 00:34:39.960
When it's at the end of a chain, it's an aldehyde.

00:34:42.300 --> 00:34:46.500
So to name this particular ketone, it's called propanone.

00:34:48.579 --> 00:34:52.280
Think of propane for a three-carbon alkane.

00:34:52.760 --> 00:34:56.079
So a three-carbon ketone is going to be propanone.

00:34:56.659 --> 00:34:59.360
Ketones have the suffix, o and e.

00:35:01.460 --> 00:35:04.320
So notice the difference between a ketone and an aldehyde.

00:35:06.039 --> 00:35:08.699
A ketone will have the carbonyl group in the middle.

00:35:10.379 --> 00:35:14.619
An aldehyde will have the carbonyl group at the end.

00:35:18.559 --> 00:35:23.780
So an aldehyde has a hydrogen that's attached to the carbonyl group.

00:35:24.219 --> 00:35:29.019
A ketone does not have the hydrogen attached to the carbonyl group.

00:35:29.780 --> 00:35:36.880
And that's how you can distinguish a ketone from an aldehyde, even though they both have the carbonyl functional group.

00:35:39.699 --> 00:35:40.619
Now here's the next one.

00:35:40.880 --> 00:35:52.699
CH3, CO2, CH3, versus CH3, and then CH2, times 3, CO2H.

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:57.800
Go ahead and draw the Lewis structures for those two molecules.

00:36:00.239 --> 00:36:02.480
So I'm not going to completely draw it out.

00:36:02.559 --> 00:36:05.440
I'm going to expand the condensed structures.

00:36:06.699 --> 00:36:10.860
So instead of Rianc with three hydrogens, I'm going to leave it as CH3.

00:36:12.320 --> 00:36:14.039
Now I'm going to expand this part.

00:36:15.740 --> 00:36:19.099
It's not going to be like this because carbon doesn't have four bonds.

00:36:20.699 --> 00:36:23.460
Instead, the CH3 is going to be attached to a carbon.

00:36:23.780 --> 00:36:28.920
We're going to have a carbonyl group, and then an oxygen attached to a CH3.

00:36:30.260 --> 00:36:33.260
So this functional group is known as an ester.

00:36:33.260 --> 00:36:40.119
An ester has two oxygen atoms, and it has a carbonyl group.

00:36:42.019 --> 00:36:49.639
On the right, we have a CH3, that's a methyl group, and then we have three methylene groups.

00:36:50.760 --> 00:36:54.019
So CH2, CH2, CH2.

00:36:56.059 --> 00:37:01.239
And then we have CO2H, which you can write as COOH.

00:37:01.239 --> 00:37:03.739
But we're going to expand that further.

00:37:04.280 --> 00:37:07.099
So we're going to have a carbonyl group and the hydroxy group.

00:37:09.019 --> 00:37:12.579
So when you combine a carbonyl group and a hydroxy group like that,

00:37:13.039 --> 00:37:16.980
you get a functional group called a carboxylic acid.

00:37:21.300 --> 00:37:26.559
Now that particular carboxylic acid has a total of five carbon atoms.

00:37:26.559 --> 00:37:30.139
A five-carbon alcanus known as hexane.

00:37:31.260 --> 00:37:34.559
So a five-carbon carbonyl acid is going to be called...

00:37:35.900 --> 00:37:37.320
Wait, let me take that back.

00:37:37.860 --> 00:37:40.599
A five-carbon alcanus not hexane, but pentane.

00:37:41.059 --> 00:37:42.179
Hexane has six carbons.

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:48.800
So a five-carbon carbonyl acid is going to be called pentanobic acid.

00:37:51.960 --> 00:37:54.659
So that's how you can name that particular carbonyl acid.

00:37:54.659 --> 00:37:59.059
Now as for the ester, we have a methyl group.

00:38:02.920 --> 00:38:08.659
And then here, we have a two-carbon group with two octgens,

00:38:09.320 --> 00:38:12.360
which is called ethanoate.

00:38:14.059 --> 00:38:18.460
So combine, this is called methyl ethanoate.

00:38:19.699 --> 00:38:22.139
If you want more examples on how to name esters,

00:38:22.139 --> 00:38:28.219
just type in ester and nomenclature in the YouTube search bar.

00:38:28.860 --> 00:38:32.760
And you'll see some videos come up that has more examples on how to name esters.

00:38:33.460 --> 00:38:34.860
But that's how you can name this particular one.

00:38:35.159 --> 00:38:37.159
It's called methyl ethanoate.

00:38:38.620 --> 00:38:40.380
Now here's a challenge problem.

00:38:42.599 --> 00:38:48.519
Go ahead and expand this particular structure.

00:38:52.139 --> 00:38:55.699
You don't have to worry about naming it, but go ahead and expand it.

00:38:57.340 --> 00:39:01.920
What I would do is I would start with the CH group there.

00:39:02.739 --> 00:39:07.380
So we have a carbon attached to a hydrogen,

00:39:08.539 --> 00:39:12.000
and then that carbon has two methyl groups attached to it.

00:39:13.300 --> 00:39:16.760
So we have one over here, and then another one on top.

00:39:18.019 --> 00:39:20.460
So this CH is the CH that we see here.

00:39:21.039 --> 00:39:25.679
And then to the right, there is another CH next to it.

00:39:26.780 --> 00:39:30.860
So I'm going to put carbon with a hydrogen.

00:39:31.699 --> 00:39:33.280
So that's the CH of this group.

00:39:33.960 --> 00:39:39.360
And then the attached to that is an OH, which we can put here, and then a CH tree.

00:39:40.719 --> 00:39:42.699
The CH trees are the methyl groups.

00:39:42.920 --> 00:39:47.000
They're always at the end of a structure, never in the middle.

00:39:47.000 --> 00:39:55.119
So the CH groups tend to branch out, and CH2 groups tend to be in the middle of a structure.

00:39:56.000 --> 00:39:57.000
So let me give you another example.

00:39:58.079 --> 00:40:07.960
So let's say we have CH3, times 3, and then the carbon, and then a CH with a BR,

00:40:07.960 --> 00:40:17.940
and then a CH2, and then another CH2, times 2, followed by a CH tree.

00:40:18.739 --> 00:40:20.400
Go ahead and expand that structure.

00:40:21.880 --> 00:40:23.960
So for this one, I'm going to start with the carbon atom.

00:40:25.320 --> 00:40:28.599
That carbon has three methyl groups connected to it.

00:40:29.780 --> 00:40:31.099
So here's the first one.

00:40:31.719 --> 00:40:35.880
Here is the second one, and here is the third one.

00:40:36.539 --> 00:40:38.219
Next, we have a CH group.

00:40:38.679 --> 00:40:41.019
So I'm going to put a carbon, and then the hydrogen.

00:40:41.980 --> 00:40:45.360
And then there's a bromine atom, which is going to be attached to this carbon,

00:40:45.760 --> 00:40:48.280
because carbon likes to form four bonds.

00:40:49.320 --> 00:40:51.800
Next, we have a CH2 group, which tends to be in the middle.

00:40:52.460 --> 00:40:54.420
So that's a carbon with two hydrogen atoms.

00:40:55.460 --> 00:40:57.619
And then we have two more CH2 groups.

00:40:59.139 --> 00:41:02.159
Here's the first one, and here is the second one.

00:41:02.159 --> 00:41:05.000
And then we have a CH3 group at the end.

00:41:08.019 --> 00:41:11.719
So that's how you can quickly expand a structure that looks like that.

00:41:12.699 --> 00:41:18.260
So keep in mind, the methyl groups are at the end of a structure like this.

00:41:20.179 --> 00:41:26.519
The CH2 groups, they're in the middle, and the CH groups tend to branch off.

00:41:26.960 --> 00:41:30.559
They're all in the middle, but they tend to have other special elements touched

00:41:30.559 --> 00:41:32.980
with a bromine or an OH group.

